{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614498"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:45:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:45:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16368"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16368"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.04,0.08,0.6,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9059"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74583"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9059"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16368"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60075"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7194"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21538"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21541"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74583"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe olfactory and optic nerves arise from the cerebrum. The other 10 paired nerves arise from the brainstem.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cranial nerves exits from the dorsal surface of the brainstem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trigeminal nerve (CN V)","Facial nerve (CN VII)","Optic nerve (CN II)","Trochlear nerve (CN IV)","Abducens nerve (CN VI)"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etrochlear nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN IV) is unique among cranial nerves as it is the only one that exits from the dorsal aspect of the brainstem, specifically at the level of the inferior colliculus. After emerging, it loops around the brainstem and travels through the subarachnoid space to innervate the superior oblique muscle of the eye. It has the longest intracranial course of all cranial nerves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etrigeminal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN V) emerges from the lateral aspect of the pons on the ventral surface of the brainstem. Its supply is sensory to the face and motor to the muscles of mastication\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efacial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN VII) exits from the ventral surface of the brainstem at the cerebellopontine angle. It provides motor innervation to the muscles of facial expression and carries taste fibres from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoptic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN II) exits the orbit through the optic canal and does not emerge from the brainstem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eabducens nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN VI) emerges from the ventral surface of the brainstem at the junction of the pons and medulla. It innervates the lateral rectus muscle of the eye.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cranial nerve IV (trochlear nerve) is the only cranial nerve that exits from the dorsal surface of the brainstem.","The trochlear nerve has the longest intracranial course of all cranial nerves.","The trochlear nerve only innervates the superior oblique muscle of the eye."],"references":["Kim SY, Motlagh M, Naqvi IA. Neuroanatomy, Cranial Nerve 4 (Trochlear) [Updated 2023 Jul 15]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537244/","Netter, F. H. (2015).\u00a0Netter\u2019s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60075"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16368"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60075"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T15:10:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T15:11:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9059"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74583"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"